<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-077-071 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 180 779</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  August 27 1991* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>New for PCs: Digital Vision unveils frame grabber.andO;(ComputerEyes/RT) (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Buckler, Grant.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Digital Vision Inc. (Product introduction).andO;Product:   Digital Vision ComputerEyes/RT (Digitizer) (Product introduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionDigitizers.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>NEW FOR PCS: Digital Vision Unveils Frame Grabber 08/27/91 DEDHAM,MASSACHUSETTS, U.S.A., 1991 AUG 27 (NB) -- Digital Vision has announcedComputerEyes/RT, a real-time video frame grabber for the IBM PC andcompatibles.andP;  Digital Vision said the frame grabber will complement its lineof slow-scan video digitizers.andM;The frame grabber can capture images from the real world in one thirtieth ofa second, the company said.andP;  Images are captured in one-bit, eight-bit (256colors), or 24-bit (16.7 million colors) color.andM;Digital Vision is promoting the use of the new product, and of its existingproducts, in new commercial and multimedia applications.andP;  While the companyhas previously concentrated on selling to computer enthusiasts and desktoppublishers, it now plans to work with third-party developers on a variety ofother applications.andM;Paul Terrio, national sales manager, told Newsbytes his company is alreadyworking with ACS Telecom, a developer that is incorporating the DigitalVision products into a system for capturing and transmitting images.andP;  Thecompany is also working with a security systems developer, which Terrio wouldnot name, that plans to use the technology in a criminal tracking system.andM;Other possibilities include automated assembly line inspection, medicalsystems image capture, sports motion analysis, real estate databaseapplications, and custom T-shirt manufacturing, the company said.andM;Product Manager Steve Sarsfield said Digital Vision has sold some productsthrough third parties before.andP;  For example, Canon sells some of DigitalVision's older products as part of a still video kit, he said.andP;  &quot;This type ofarrangement has always worked out pretty well for us.&quot;andM;Digital Vision is offering a developer's tool kit for US$100.00.andP;  The toolkit includes an executable program that allows users to capture an image byissuing a DOS command.andP;  Microsoft C and assembler code are also included.andM;ComputerEyes/RT sells for US$599, and works with an IBM PC, XT, AT, 286, 386,486, PS/2 Models 25 or 30, or compatible computer with at least 512K bytes ofmemory, DOS 2.1 or higher, and VGA, Super-VGA, or MCGA graphics capabilities.andO;A hard drive is recommended.andM;(Grant Buckler/19910827/Press Contact: Steve Sarsfield, Digital Vision,617-329-5400)</TEXT></DOC>